  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These aren't necessarily *laws* in the sense of a global government passing them, but rather international agreements that obligate signatory nations to enact their own national laws against money laundering. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** This is the most important international standard on combating money laundering, terrorist financing and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. The FATF Recommendations set out a comprehensive and consistent framework of measures which countries should implement to combat these crimes.  While not a law itself, these recommendations are endorsed by numerous international organizations and have become the de facto global standard. Countries are assessed on their compliance with the FATF Recommendations, and non-compliance can lead to significant economic and reputational consequences.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This convention requires states to criminalize the laundering of drug money. It's a key early international agreement addressing money laundering.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):**  This convention expands the scope of money laundering offences beyond drug-related crimes to include the proceeds of a wider range of serious crimes. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds of crime and to adopt measures to confiscate the proceeds of crime.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention):** This convention requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds of corruption.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) (Strasbourg Convention):**  This is a regional convention focused on Europe. It aims to facilitate international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering and confiscating the proceeds of crime.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (2005) (Warsaw Convention):** This is an update to the Strasbourg Convention that expands its scope to include terrorist financing.\n\n**Key takeaways:**\n\n*   **No single global law:** There's no world government to enact a single, universally applicable money laundering law.\n*   **International standards and conventions:** Instead, there are international agreements that create obligations for signatory nations to enact their own laws to combat money laundering.\n*   **FATF is key:** The FATF Recommendations are the most influential global standard and drive many national laws and regulations.\n*   **Broad scope:** International agreements cover money laundering related to drug trafficking, organized crime, corruption, and terrorism.\n*   **International cooperation:** These agreements also promote international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses, including extradition, mutual legal assistance, and asset sharing.\n\nIt's important to understand that the effectiveness of these international efforts depends on the willingness and ability of individual countries to implement and enforce their own anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations.  Countries that fail to do so can become safe havens for illicit funds.\n",
